P2: Investage a dataset, Titanic¶

After following the course and looking at the project specification document I found it logical to use the data analysis phases to document how I approached this assignment. In practice it was not so straightforward. I came to the conclusion during the Wrangling phase that I had to drop a question and a lot of exploration was done as part of Question formulation and Wrangling.

Since I am not a big sports fan and know little about baseball rules, I chose the Titanic dataset.

Question phase¶

I started out with a brief examination of the dataset, reading the description of the dataset on the Kaggle website and looking at information I could find on the web about the Titanic.

After reading the dataset in the dataframe titanic_df I used the functions titanic_df.head() and titanic_df.describe() for the dataframe and titanic_df.column_name.unique() for every column in the dataframe to get more insight in the data.

The following information found on the web I found interesting:

  1. The letters in the Cabin field reference to the decks, 9 in total (counting the orlop deck) the boat deck, A,B,C,D,E,F,G and below G boiler rooms.
  2. The positions of the decks is that boat deck is on top (T-deck), followed by A until G and lowest is below G.
  3. The ports of embarkation are in the following countries in the order of the route: Southampton - England, Cherbourg - France, Queenstown - Ireland.

While examing information on the web, I read a story about a family that did not leave the Titanic because they were still looking for the baby of the family. What they did not know was that the nanny had already taken the baby in one of the lifeboats. The baby survived while the rest of the family drowned. There were also some women who refused to leave their husbands or other male relatives although they were offered room on the liveboats. These sad stories made me wonder what the influence of the size of the families has been: was there a stronger urge to stay together or a stronger sense of responsibility to save as much people as possible within the family. I know that this conclusion can not be made from the data, so I need to rephrase my question:

Question 1: What is the influence of the size of the family (in terms of the column 'Parch') on the survival rate of a person. I also want to see how this is impacted by age and sex; what has been the effect of 'Women and Children' first to the survival rates in general and was this different for families? For this I also need to come up with a definition of male children.

Question 2: Another thing that got me interested was the influence of the deck location of the cabins on the survival rate. The deck location of the cabins and the social status are probably related. That needs to be taken into account. But, I am doubtful if this question can be answered, since in the first five entries, I already see 3 null-values for Cabin.

Wrangling phase¶

I did the following things to determine the quality of the data:

  1. I examined which columns have null-values.
  2. I checked every column for unique values.
  3. I looked for outliers.
  4. I splitted the Name field in lastname, title, firstname (sometimes it contains more information then firstname). I did this to examine if there is a correlation between the title and the age. The seperate Lastname field can be helpful when selecting/sorting on Lastname.
  5. I solved the null-values for age and for embarked.
  6. I decided not to select the deck identification from the cabin identification, because the cabin column contains a large number of null values for which I could not find other data in the dataset to solve this problem
  7. I created more descriptive labels

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.title('Class Proportions')

def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        total = sum(values)
        val = int(round(pct*total/100.0))
        return '{p:.2f}%  ({v:d})'.format(p=pct,v=val)
    return my_autopct

plt.pie(titanic_df.Class.value_counts(), labels=titanic_df.Class.value_counts().index, autopct=make_autopct(titanic_df.Class.value_counts()))
plt.show()

Conclusions after investigation of data quality¶

  1. In addition to the data on kaggle, every row has an unique passengerid.
  2. There are 891 passengers in the dataset.
  3. No outliers found.
  4. The Age column contains 177 null-values.
  5. The Cabin column contains 687 null-values.
  6. The Embarked field contains 2 null-values.

  7. Besides what the description on Kaggle says about the dataset, I found the following things on the various fields:

     b. Ticket is a number or a combination or a prefix with a number.
 c. Fare is everywhere numerical. 
 d. Cabin, usually a letter (A-G) followed by 1, 2 or 3 numbers. Multiple cabins per passenger is possible. 
    Nan and T as special values.
 e. It looks like female children were marked as Miss, male children as Master.

With exception of the Dr title (probably Doctor) every title is only used by one of the sexes. There is one female Dr and there are six male Dr. The majority of the titles is used once or few times. The titles Master, Miss, Mr and Mrs are used by the 97% of the passengers. These four titles have standard deviations around 12 with exception of Master, which has a very low standard deviation of 3.62. This is logical; based on this standard deviation in combination with the mean of 4.57, my conclusion is that the Master title was given to males who were not considered adults in that time. The maximum age found for Master is 12. The Mr title is used for the older males. The average age of a Miss is 21.77 and of a Mrs 35.90, making it two distinctly different groups.

Based on this information, I find it logical to determine a missing age on the mean of the age from everybody with the same title.

For 687 of 891 passengers the Cabin or more in general the location or deck where they slept is not known. I see no possibility to get this information in an other way.

There are two people with an unknown embarkation port, Miss Amelie Icard and Mrs George Nelson. Both boarded using ticket 113572 and used cabin B28. To determine a possible embarkation port I examined if other passengers used the same ticket, if there are other people with the last ames icard, stone or nelson, or other users of cabin B28. This was not the case. On the web I found they boarded in Southhampton, so I decided to change Embarked to 'S' for both of them.

Exploration phase¶

Question 1: What is the influence of the size of the family (in terms of the column 'Parch') on the survival rate of a person. I also want to see how this is impacted by age and sex; what has been the effect of 'Women and Children' first to the survival rates in general and was this different for families? For this I also need to come up with a definition of male children.

Based on the question I chose to explore the following multiple variables, to get a better understanding in the supposed survival rates of sex and of age:

  1. survival rate per sex
  2. survival rate per age
  3. surival rate per sex per age

My conclusion is that there is a clear difference in survival rate both in terms of sex and of age; Females and younger passengers have larger survival rates. The last graph clearly shows that around the age of 15 there is a significant change in the survival rate of males. Based on this is seems likely that the principle of 'Women and children first' was followed during evacuation.

To determine the group of women and children better I want to zoom in at the survival rates of males around the age of 15 and also check if the title Master is a good definition of a male child by comparing the survival rate of passengers with the title Master to those with the title Mr.

Conclusion phase¶

Question 1: What is the influence of the size of the family (in terms of the column 'Parch') on the survival rate of a person. I also want to see how this is impacted by age and sex; what has been the effect of 'Women and Children' first to the survival rates in general and was this different for families?

I come to the following conclusions:

  1. The survival rate for the group women and children is significantly higher then the survival rate for the group adult men.
  2. For both groups the survival rate goes down when the value of the field Parch goes up. Having children and/or parents onboard lowers the probability of survival for the group examined. We can not speak of a causation here (for this I would need to do an expirement, which I can not) and since I did not perform a t-test, correlation can not be proven.
  3. The number of passengers where the value of the field Parch is bigger then 2 is very low, in total 15 over 4 different values.

Limitations of the analysis¶

Of only 714 from the 891 passengers the age was known. The unknown ages were determined based on the averages of the title carried by the passenger. This could have an impact on the survival rates per age plot. It could well be that the principle 'Women, children and elderly' was followed. Of this we cannot be sure, elderly with unkwown age are now counted as average age.

Since correlation is not proven with a t-test, we are not sure if the results are by change or not.

What would have been interesting data, is more detailed information on relationships between the passengers. Knowing which passengers all belong to the same group allows to examine group behaviour. This can not be done based on count of number of parents/children. Maybe this information could have been subtracted during wrangling, but I did not examine this.

Communication phase¶

I wanted to know if the survival rate of a passenger on the Titanic was different based on the number of parents and /or children of these passengers. Because there the rule 'Women and children first' was applied on board of the Titanic, I compared the survival rates for women and children on the one hand and adult males on the other hand. Both groups exclude one another and both groups together form the complete population for which data was available.

The results are shown in the two histograms below.

Both histograms show that the survival rate lowers when the number of parents and/or children grows. There is one exception and that is in the histogram women and children where the number of parents and/or children equals 3. Here the survival rate rises and breaks a downward trend. The number of passengers with number of parents and/or children that equal 3 or more is very low, in total 15 on a population of 891. The impact of one extra survivor is therefore enough to cause the breaking of the trend.

The conclusion therefore is that there is a negative correlation between survival rate and the number of parents and/or children per passenger.
